du/entries/weber/">"Max Weber"</a>. Stanford Encyclopaedia of Philosophy<span class="printonly">. <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/weber/">http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/weber/</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved 17 February 2010</span>.</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-WeberGerth1991-4"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-WeberGerth1991_4-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-WeberGerth1991_4-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation book">Max Weber; Hans Heinrich Gerth; Bryan S. Turner (7 March 1991). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://books.google.com/books?id=Y_pqZS5q72UC&pg=PR1"><i>From Max Weber: essays in sociology</i></a>. Psychology Press. p.&#160;1. <a href="International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="Special_BookSources/978-0-415-06056-1" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-415-06056-1">978-0-415-06056-1</a><span class="printonly">. <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://books.google.com/books?id=Y_pqZS5q72UC&pg=PR1">http://books.google.com/books?id=Y_pqZS5q72UC&amp;pg=PR1</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved 22 March 2011</span>.</span></span></li>
